2018 Ford GoBike System Data¶

by Deborah Micael¶

Preliminary Wrangling¶

This data set includes information about individual rides made in a bike-sharing system covering the greater San Francisco Bay area (San Francisco, East Bay, San Jose). This dataset requires some data wrangling in order to make it tidy for analysis. There are multiple data files that will need to be joined together for a full year’s coverage.

df['start_time'] = pd.to_datetime(df['start_time'])

Given that the trip duration is in seconds, it needs to be converted to minutes, a more natural unit of analysis¶
In [8]:
df['duration_min'] = df['duration_sec']/60
Split datetime values into different columns¶
In [9]:
#Display start time month
df['start_time_month'] = df['start_time'].dt.month
#Display start time hour
df['start_time_hour'] = df['start_time'].dt.hour
#Display start time day
df['start_time_day'] = df['start_time'].dt.weekday_name
Reorder the start time weekdays, a more natural order¶
In [10]:
df['start_time_day'] = pd.Categorical(df['start_time_day'], 
                        categories=['Monday','Tuesday','Wednesday','Thursday','Friday','Saturday', 'Sunday'], ordered=True)
Create trip column that concatenates the start and end stations¶
In [11]:
df['trip'] = df['start_station_name'].str.cat(df['end_station_name'], sep=' to ')

#Replace Null values with 'None'
df['trip']= df.trip.fillna('None')
Calculate the distance between the start and end stations¶
In [12]:
df['trip_distance_km'] = df.apply(lambda x: haversine((x['start_station_latitude'], 
                            x['start_station_longitude']), (x['end_station_latitude'], 
                            x['end_station_longitude']), unit='km'), axis=1)

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The raw combined 2018 Ford GoBike System Data contains 1,863,721 rows (trips) and 14 columns which was reduced to 8 columns. The column names are shown above.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

The main features of interest are as follows:

  • Popular times of travel (i.e. occurs most often in the start time)
  • Trip duration
  • Trip distance
  • Behavior of subscribers vs customers

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

The features of interest are shown in the above cell.

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

Overall, the trip duration distribution is skewed to the right with a mean at 10 minutes and outliers above 27 minutes. The distance distribution is also skewed to the right with a mean at 1.5 km and outliers at 4 km or more. An overwhelming number of users are subscribers. Overall, the monthly bike ride gradually increased and plateaued, peaking in October. The hourly bike trend is binomial with peaks at 8 AM and 7 PM. While the highest peak is on Tuesday, followed by Wednesday and Thursday, the lowest peaks are the weekend. The most popular trip is from the San Francisco Ferry Building (Harry Bridges Plaza) to the Embarcadero at Sansome St. Yes, transformations are needed to be performed given the unusual duration and distance distributions.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

The trip duration and distance distributions revealed outliers, some of which were very extreme. Therefore, they were removed. Given that the trip duration is in seconds, it was converted to minutes because it is a more natural unit of analysis. In addition, the start time was converted into the datetime format so that the datetime values can be split into different columns. The start time weekdays were reordered to a more natural order. A trip column was created by concatenating the start and end stations and replacing the null values with 'None'.

Trip Duration vs Trip Distance¶

There appears to be a positive strong linear correlation between trip distance and trip duration. There is no correlation between trip distance and trip duration which may be due to the use of both electric and regular bikes.

#Create heatmap function
def heatmap(a,b,c,d,e):
    #Create customer and subscriber data frames and restrict the start time hours to only include the peak hours
    customer_h= df[(df['user_type']=='Customer') & (df['start_time_hour']>=7) & (df['start_time_hour']<=10)| 
                   (df['start_time_hour'] >= 16) & (df['start_time_hour'] <= 19)].groupby([a,b]).agg({'bike_id': 
                                                    'count'}).rename(columns={'bike_id':'count'}).reset_index()
    
    subscriber_h= df[(df['user_type']=='Subscriber') & (df['start_time_hour']>=7) & (df['start_time_hour']<=10)|
                     (df['start_time_hour'] >= 16) & (df['start_time_hour'] <= 19)].groupby([a,b]).agg({'bike_id':
                                                    'count'}).rename(columns={'bike_id':'count'}).reset_index()
    
    #Create customer and subscriber percent and rank columns
    customer_h['count_perc'] = customer_h['count'].apply(lambda x: (x/customer_h['count'].sum())*100)
    customer_h['rank'] = customer_h['count_perc'].rank(ascending=False).astype(int)
    customer_h_df_pivoted = customer_h.pivot_table(index=b, columns=a, values='rank').astype(int)
    
    subscriber_h['count_perc'] = subscriber_h['count'].apply(lambda x: (x/subscriber_h['count'].sum())*100)
    subscriber_h['rank'] = subscriber_h['count_perc'].rank(ascending=False).astype(int)
    subscriber_h_df_pivoted = subscriber_h.pivot_table(index=b, columns=a, values='rank').astype(int)
    
    #Create heatmaps
    plt.figure(figsize=(15,5))
    plt.subplot(1,2,1)
    plt.suptitle(c, fontsize=16)
    sb.heatmap(customer_h_df_pivoted, annot=True, fmt='d', cbar_kws={'label': 'Rank of Frequency'}) 
    plt.title('Customers', fontsize=14)
    plt.xlabel(d, fontsize=14)
    plt.ylabel(e, fontsize=14)
    plt.yticks(rotation=360)
    b, t = plt.ylim() # discover the values for bottom and top
